title: For Sale:  1941 - SVT 40 - 7.62 X 54R semi auto Better than a PSL!
postcontent:
As the description says, I am listing up my Russian SVT 40 for sale. Chances are if your looking at this listing, you know what this rifle is. Russia's rare semi-auto rifle from World War Two. These are rather rare to come across unlike the millions of Mosin Nagant's we are all  accustomed to seeing everywhere. This rifle is surprisingly accurate and has strong rifling down the barrel (see photos). Its obviously in used condition as these rifles were shipped out for use as fast as they could be made. This particular rifle was bought from a veteran's collection and was a bring back rifle from either Korea or Vietnam. There are no import marks on it at all but like most of these rifles I'm guessing it went back through the arsenal after WW2 for a general look over and to be maintained to replace any worn parts. Most but not all of the numbers are matching and the action is extremely- almost surprisingly smooth. I have quite a few Russian rifles and this is by far the smoothest. I've owned a PSL before as well and This is by far a better shooter.

Since buying it about two years ago, I only have shot about 5-6 rounds through it. Its mostly been a safe queen and also a great piece to bring out to show and talk about. However at the range, the rifle shot just fine and all of the rounds ended up on target with a pretty good grouping for its age.. within about a drink coaster 4" or so maybe? I have not and did not adjust the iron sights since I bought it and at 100 or so yards, its pretty spot on but I'm sure with the right ammo and or optics, it would be a nail driver. 

It comes with one 10 round magazine, sold as is, and is an awesome piece of history. This is one rifle that most people have read about, but not everyone has seen or held let alone shot. This is your chance to own one. 

I'm primarily looking for cash. That being said, I will entertain the a trade plus cash if the deal is really right. Interested in Saiga 12's, WW2 firearms (Lugar pistols) & Unusual and rare firearms- however they must be able to shoot modern day ammo that is easily accessible. I enjoy my firearm collection as one would enjoy a collection of high end cars and believe that If you cant get out and drive them, what's the point. :-) 

Looking forward to hearing from serious buyers. Low ballers and tire kickers, please move on! If you would like more photos email me and let me know what you would like to see in particular and also please include your email address for me so I can get additional photos over to you.

Have a great day and thanks for checking out my listing!
